Fig. 2a illustrates the XRD patterns of CQDs, CdS and CQDs/CdS. The broad peak is appeared at around 22° which looks like to a graphite lattice spacing. The hydrothermal process is an effective method for synthesizing CQDs with rich active sites on their surface. [22]. Also, The XRD results of CdS and CQDs/CdS samples revealed excellent crystallinity of its hexagonal pure phase which can be indexed based on JCPDS file No. 06-0464 [22]. The XRD peaks of CQDs have not been observed in CQDs/CdS, because less content of CQDs in the CQDs/CdS. Furthermore, the molding of CdS has not been changed by adding CQDs. The crystallite sizes was estimated using Scherrer equation ( D = kλ /
β cos θ
). These results showed that the crystallite size of CdS, CQDs/CdS, and RGO/CdS are 36.98, 36.57, and 37.35 nm respectively. The percent of sample crystallinity (% crystallinity) can be calculated from the ratio of the integrated crystalline peaks area to the total integrated area under the XRD peaks. Crystallinity index is the ratio of the crystalline peaks to the crystalline + amorphous peaks. Amorphous peaks are related to the noise in XRD data, while crystalline + amorphous correspond to the whole XRD profile. So, % Crystallinity = Ic / (Ic + Ia) ∗ 100 where Ia and Ic are the integrated intensities corresponding to the amorphous and crystalline phases, respectively. According to related data, % crystallinity of CdS and CQDs/CdS are 40.48 %, and 40.78 %, respectively.
